context: The <a0_0><b5_0>Revolutionary War soldier<b5_0/><a0_0/> Nathan Hale (Yale 1773) was the prototype of the Yale ideal in the early 19th century: a manly yet aristocratic scholar, equally well-versed in knowledge and sports, and a patriot who "regretted" that he "had but one life to lose" for his country. Western painter Frederic Remington (Yale 1900) was an <a1_0><b6_0>artist<b6_0/><a1_0/> whose <a4_0><b9_0>heroes gloried in combat and tests of strength in the Wild West<b9_0/><a4_0/>. The fictional, turn-of-the-20th-century Yale man Frank Merriwell embodied the heroic ideal without racial prejudice, and his fictional successor <a2_0><b7_0>Frank Stover<b7_0/><a2_0/> in the novel Stover at Yale (1911) questioned the business mentality that had become prevalent at the school. Increasingly the students turned to athletic stars as their heroes, especially since <a3_0><b8_0>winning the big game<b8_0/><a3_0/> became the goal of the student body, and the alumni, as well as the team itself.
